snippet.textDisplay:
I want to like this movie, I really do, but I get the feeling that this movie is based on actual events in the same way "Saving Private Ryan" was. In that movie, they took a story about five real brothers who died on the same ship in the Pacific and turned it into a story that never happened or could have happened at Normandy.

Similarly, I can think of three different major convoy battles with fascinating stories that this movie is probably based on, and it doesn't seem to be telling any of them. It seems to be telling the story of how Tom Hanks won WW2 again; "There was these U-boats, dozens of them, and they surfaced right in front of me and I was all like "Blammo" and blew them to pieces!

You mean the U-boats that the allies desperately wanted to capture so we could study them? There are only a few captains I can think of who deserve merit for innovative tactics against U-boats, and none of them are whoever the hell Hanks is supposed to be portraying.

Historical accuracy seems to have gone out the window unless I'm missing something, so I hope the film will at least manage to be fun and not have some kind of stupid left-wing social message heavier than any warship. I bet it will be there, though, somewhere. Hollywood always manages to stick them in there with films like these. They just can't learn from the success of films like Midway, Tora Tora Tora, and Das Boot, that they aren't better at telling stories than the actual historical events. They can dress and polish them, but they'll never be better than the real thing.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have not been a particular fan of Tom Hanks - not even Saving Private Ryan or Castaway - but him doing a movie about this (sadly overlooked, vital) story is probably going to make me one.


I can remember one of my 1950s war comics having a story about a convoy necessarily defended by only a few escorts. Grim.


Looking forward to the movie, Tom! (Steve Spielberg have anything to do with this? :-) )


Historical note: It was our pre-war Benson and Gleaves etc. fleet destroyers ... and World War 1 4-stackers ... and Coast Guard cutters ... assigned to the early convoys. Our first-line Fletchers were all top priority to the Pacific, but that's not crucial to the beautiful intent of the film.

snippet.textDisplay: This looks pretty good, though certain bits seem a little far-fetched. I'm looking forward to it anyway. For the best WWII convoy escort vs. U-Boats movie the film 'The Cruel Sea' is the one to beat. It's not only a great historical account, based on the novelist's experiences being an officer in a corvette during the Atlantic War, but it's a taut, emotional, unsentimental, brutal, lyrical yet unromantic look at a war against a hidden enemy, an enemy most times you're never even sure you actually sunk or not. Jack Hawkins and Donald Sinden completely rock the film as Captain and First Lieutenant. Alongside Das Boot, it's a must see.
